   =20
      Bad robot
   =20
 =20
In 2015, Charles Schwab Corp. launched a robo-adviser service called Schwab=
 Intelligent Portfolios.=C2=A0SIP would would invest customers=E2=80=99=C2=
=A0money for them in a mix of funds optimized for their risk appetite, inve=
stment horizon and tax situation. Unlike competing robo-advisers, SIP would=
 not charge customers a fee for this service. Instead, it would allocate a =
bizarrely large portion of their portfolios to cash, and it would keep the =
cash in a Schwab-affiliated bank account paying (initially) 0.1% interest. =
Schwab could use this cash to earn a higher rate and keep the difference, m=
aking this product profitable for Schwab. Other robo-advisers did not alloc=
ate so much to cash, because=C2=A0they are investing products; most custome=
rs keep their cash in bank accounts and want their investments to be invest=
ed. But the other robo-advisers charged fees.Schwab=E2=80=99s approach was =
good marketing, but bad for investors: You=E2=80=99d rather be 100% in the =
market while this was going on (2015 through 2018) and pay a fee than be 80=
% in the market and 20% in cash earning nothing. It was also sort of weirdl=
y well-known: I remember it being controversial at the time, and here is a =
good New York Times article by Tara Siegel Bernard from March 2015, when SI=
P launched, headlined =E2=80=9CSchwab=E2=80=99s Service for Investors Seeki=
ng Thrifty Advice Raises Eyebrows=E2=80=9D and laying out the problem clear=
ly. But Schwab was cagey about it, saying that actually those cash allocati=
ons were intended to be good for customers rather than just to make a buck.=
Yesterday=C2=A0Schwab=C2=A0agreed to pay $187 million to settle US Securiti=
es and Exchange Commission charges for deceiving investors over SIP, and th=
e SEC order is just so embarrassing:Each of SIP=E2=80=99s model portfolios =
held between 6% and 29.4% of clients=E2=80=99 assets in cash. The amount of=
 cash that each SIP model portfolio contained was pre-set so that Responden=
ts=E2=80=99 affiliate bank would earn at least a minimum amount of revenue =
from the spread on the cash by loaning out the money. ...In order to offer =
SIP without charging an advisory fee, Schwab management decided that the SI=
P portfolios would collectively hold an average of at least 12.5% of their =
assets in cash. To meet that goal, management set the exact amount of cash =
in each of SIP=E2=80=99s model portfolios, with the most aggressive portfol=
io containing 6% cash and the most conservative portfolio 29.4%, based in l=
arge part on its analysis that Schwab Bank would make a minimum amount of r=
evenue at these levels. Management then provided these pre-set cash allocat=
ions to CSIA. In building the SIP model portfolios, CSIA treated the cash a=
llocations provided by management as constraints and did not alter or adjus=
t the cash allocations in any way. ...On February 18, 2015, weeks before th=
e SIP launch, two articles were published in the media that were critical o=
f SIP, claiming that the drag from the high cash allocations was a hidden c=
ost of the program. In reaction to these articles, Schwab management direct=
ed that the SWIA ADV brochure be re-written, and that a public relations ca=
mpaign be launched to explain the SIP cash allocations. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Whil=
e the ADV brochures disclosed that Schwab Bank earned income from the cash =
allocation for each investment strategy, SWIA=E2=80=99s and CSIA=E2=80=99s =
ADV brochures stated that the cash allocations in the SIP portfolios were =
=E2=80=9Cset based on a disciplined portfolio construction methodology desi=
gned to balance performance with risk management appropriate for a client=
=E2=80=99s goal, investing time frame, and personal risk tolerance, just as=
 with other Schwab managed products.=E2=80=9D This was false and misleading=
 because the cash allocations were actually pre-set in order to reach minim=
um revenue targets for the Respondents.=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t know. They got=
 so close, you know? It is such a basic move in finance: Find a way to do a=
 valuable thing=C2=A0without charging for it explicitly, because you have f=
ound a way to charge for it implicitly. Schwab=C2=A0could=C2=A0have done th=
is in a more or less legal way: Say =E2=80=9Cwe will charge zero fees and=
=C2=A0construct a portfolio for you using a disciplined methodology that is=
 appropriate for your goals, period, new sentence,=C2=A0also we will alloca=
te a portion of your money to cash for other reasons.=E2=80=9D And then, wh=
en people write articles about how the cash allocation is too high and repr=
esents a big fee for Schwab,=C2=A0just ignore them. Who cares! Some people =
will read the articles and not use SIP; Schwab probably would not attract t=
hose people by lying anyway. Some people will read the articles=C2=A0and st=
ill use SIP, thinking =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t like explicit fees and havin=
g a cash drag seems fine.=E2=80=9D (Doesn=E2=80=99t a cash drag seem like a=
 good idea this month?) Many, many people will not read the articles at all=
, and those people will be attracted by the zero explicit fees and not worr=
y about the implicit ones.Really Schwab=E2=80=99s mistake was pride: It had=
 figured out a way to hide fees in an investment product, people noticed an=
d said =E2=80=9Chey there are hidden fees,=E2=80=9D and Schwab=E2=80=99s ma=
nagement got mad and publicly pretended that those hidden fees were somethi=
ng else. Seems unnecessary. Just smile and say =E2=80=9Cwell we all have to=
 make money somehow=E2=80=9D and trust that you=E2=80=99ve hidden the fees =
well enough for most customers.Also I should say that this is a problem tha=
t I knew about in 2015, because I read the New York Times? It is nice that =
the SEC got $187 million back for investors who were tricked by this, but c=
ould they not have done it faster?
