      Banker chats
   =20
 =20
One basic element of the job of a banker or salesperson is that you want to=
 befriend your clients. You don=E2=80=99t have to have a real, close friend=
ship with every client, but in general the more your clients feel that they=
 have social and personal ties to you, the better off you are. A lot of wha=
t you are doing is fairly commoditized, so it is good for clients to feel s=
ome sense of personal obligation to you so that they=E2=80=99ll send that b=
usiness to you rather than to one of your dozen interchangeable competitors=
. And a lot of what isn=E2=80=99t commoditized is=C2=A0complicated or risky=
; if your clients trust you personally =E2=80=94=C2=A0if they think of you =
not as a salesperson for Bank X but as a person whom they know and like =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0then they will be more likely to buy complicated or risky stuff=
 from=C2=A0 you.It is possible to build a personal rapport with a client ex=
clusively using emails from your work account, Bloomberg chats and phone ca=
lls from a recorded office line. People do this all the time. Traditionally=
, though, there is also an element of going out for dinner or drinks or gol=
f or sporting events. These things are complicated; plenty of clients don=
=E2=80=99t=C2=A0want=C2=A0to spend their after-work time hanging out with s=
alespeople, and in many cases you will build a better rapport by keeping ev=
erything on business channels during business hours. But certainly a lot of=
 people try the dinners-and-drinks approach, which suggests that it often w=
orks.=C2=A0One vague theory that I have is that due to (1) Covid-19 and (2)=
 everyone being increasingly online all the time anyway, there has been som=
e substitution here, where now the way to signify a personal friendship wit=
h clients is not so much playing golf with them but rather following them o=
n Instagram or messaging them on WhatsApp or whatever. Like, in either case=
 what you are doing is something in the category of =E2=80=9Changing out wi=
th the client in non-work ways, thus deepening your personal relationship.=
=E2=80=9D And in either case you are of course mixing work and non-work: Wh=
en you are golfing together, you do not discuss deals=C2=A0much, but you di=
scuss deals=C2=A0a little, and your discussions are especially impactful be=
cause you are on the golf course together so you must be friends. Same in t=
he Instagram DMs or whatever.=C2=A0That is not the only thing going on here=
, but I do think that it is=C2=A0a=C2=A0thing going on here:A senior Credit=
 Suisse investment banker was removed from his position earlier this year a=
fter he was found to have used unapproved messaging applications with clien=
ts, according to people with knowledge of the matter.Anthony Kontoleon, kno=
wn as =E2=80=9CAK=E2=80=9D to colleagues, was Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s globa=
l head of equity capital markets syndicate in New York and left his positio=
n in April. He is set to depart the bank, where he has worked for 28 years.=
The action taken by Credit Suisse comes amid a US government investigation =
of record-keeping practices across Wall Street.Credit Suisse decided to rem=
ove Kontoleon from his role after an audit of several dozen of its bankers =
found that he had used personal messaging applications to communicate with =
clients, the people added. The audit did not find that Kontoleon had shared=
 any inappropriate information. =E2=80=A6Syndicate desks, such as the one w=
here Kontoleon worked, are attracted to text messaging for quick and easy c=
ommunication because they are in constant dialogue with hedge fund and asse=
t management clients about stock sales and market activity.The practice bec=
ame more common when bankers started working from home during the Covid-19 =
crisis.=E2=80=9CDuring the pandemic, people got so accustomed to just texti=
ng outside of the controlled environment,=E2=80=9D said one senior Wall Str=
eet banker.There are lots of reasons to use unregulated messaging apps to c=
ommunicate with clients. One is that they are quick and easy, possibly quic=
ker than using your work email or other official channels. I guess another =
is that you can do secret crimes on those apps, though I doubt that that is=
 relevant for=C2=A0most=C2=A0people. But a third is that if you have a clie=
nt=E2=80=99s personal cell number you are just a little bit closer to that =
client than if you are emailing her on her work email, and that is good. Ex=
cept that it=E2=80=99s also bad.One question about unapproved texting apps =
is how much they substitute for official text-based electronic communicatio=
ns like email (which are traditionally preserved, monitored, easily searcha=
ble, heavily regulated), how much they substitute for telephone=C2=A0commun=
ications (which are often but not always preserved, and somewhat less legib=
le to regulators), and how much they substitute for in-person=C2=A0communic=
ations (which are basically invisible to regulators). If you used to sit ar=
ound with your colleagues making jokes and discussing business in person, a=
nd then you all started working from home and making jokes and discussing b=
usiness in a WhatsApp chat, you=E2=80=99re not really hiding=C2=A0anything =
that you weren=E2=80=99t hiding already: Either way, you are making the jok=
es and discussing the business in ways that are not electronically monitore=
d by your bank. But talking in person seems so normal that no one could obj=
ect, while chatting=C2=A0on WhatsApp will get you in a lot of trouble.
