   =20
      ESG
   =20
 =20
I suppose a minimal form=C2=A0of =E2=80=9Cenvironmental, social and governa=
nce investing=E2=80=9D would be =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t invest in fossil-fue=
l producers.=E2=80=9D There is a lot wrong with that, as a definition of ES=
G. Many thoughtful ESG investors would say that you=C2=A0should=C2=A0invest=
 in fossil-fuel producers: You pick the=C2=A0best=C2=A0fossil-fuel producer=
s (the ones best positioned for a climate transition)=C2=A0and give them yo=
ur money, to incentivize good behavior, or maybe you pick the=C2=A0worst=C2=
=A0ones and do activism to try to change their policies. And of course =E2=
=80=9CESG=E2=80=9D means a lot of things other than carbon emissions; you=
=E2=80=99ve got S and G right there in the name, so you might want to avoid=
, say, green tech companies with bad governance or bad labor relations or w=
hatever. Still the most salient thing is pretty much fossil-fuel production=
, and a crude expectation is that ESG funds will avoid fossil-fuel companie=
s.This creates an opportunity:=09Lots of funds don=E2=80=99t invest in foss=
il-fuel companies, not because they are =E2=80=9CESG=E2=80=9D but because t=
hey are, you know,=C2=A0tech=C2=A0funds, or healthcare funds, or consumer f=
unds, or whatever: They invest in some sector or style that excludes the en=
ergy sector. Are big tech companies all =E2=80=9CESG=E2=80=9D? Well, you co=
uld have various complaints about their governance or social impact or even=
 their environmental impact, but they are all indisputably not fossil-fuel =
producers.=09ESG is hot right now.=09Call your tech fund an ESG fund, why n=
ot, it meets that minimal definition of ESG. You don=E2=80=99t have to do a=
nything different, but now=C2=A0you can raise lots of money from investors =
who want an ESG fund.The US Securities and Exchange Commission is investiga=
ting Goldman Sachs Group Inc. over its ESG marketing:The SEC=E2=80=99s civi=
l investigation is focused on Goldman=E2=80=99s mutual-funds business, the =
people said, and the firm manages at least four funds that have clean-energ=
y or ESG in their names. The probe could end without formal enforcement act=
ion.Regulators have sometimes expressed concerns that ESG=E2=80=94which doe=
sn=E2=80=99t have a defined regulatory meaning=E2=80=94can be a superficial=
 way to market financial products to shareholders=E2=80=99 desire to addres=
s subjects such as climate change or diversity in the workplace. =E2=80=A6G=
oldman renamed its Blue Chip Fund as the U.S. Equity ESG Fund in June 2020.=
 The fund=E2=80=99s top three holdings=E2=80=94Microsoft Corp., Apple Inc.,=
 and Alphabet Inc.=E2=80=94-have remained the same since then, according to=
 regulatory filings. The U.S. Equity ESG fund=E2=80=99s other top holdings =
currently include Bristol-Myers Squibb Co., Eli Lilly & Co., and JPMorgan C=
hase & Co., according to its website.=C2=A0None of those are oil companies!=
 Seems fine.
 =20
   =20
      Insider trading
   =20
 =20
=E2=80=9CSEC Charges Former Employee of Online Gambling Company with Inside=
r Trading,=E2=80=9D it says here, and I got excited.=C2=A0Recently  we disc=
ussed a sort of broad theory of insider trading, in which misusing your emp=
loyer=E2=80=99s material nonpublic information to make any sort of bet coul=
d be loosely characterized as =E2=80=9Cinsider trading.=E2=80=9D If you wor=
k at a non-fungible token marketplace and buy NFTs with inside information,=
 sure, insider trading. If you work at=C2=A0an online gambling company and =
you do some online gambling with inside information, sure, insider trading.=
 Maybe not a matter for the US Securities and Exchange Commission, but stil=
l, a kind of insider trading =E2=80=94=C2=A0misusing confidential informati=
on, undermining confidence in (gambling) markets =E2=80=94 that prosecutors=
 might care about.But, no, this is just regular insider trading, in stock. =
Well, not stock per se; like so much regular insider trading, this is insid=
er trading in short-dated out-of-the-money call options on the stock of a m=
erger target:The SEC=E2=80=99s complaint, filed in federal district court i=
n Philadelphia, alleges that, while employed at Penn Interactive, which pro=
vides online and mobile gambling experiences for Penn National, [David] Rod=
a was given confidential information about Penn National=E2=80=99s interest=
 in acquiring Score Media along with admonitions not to trade on that infor=
mation. In breach of his duties, Roda purchased 500 out-of-the-money call o=
ptions on Score Media in the weeks and days leading up to the announcement =
of the acquisition. Additionally, Roda tipped his longtime friend, Andrew L=
arkin, also charged by the SEC, who then purchased 375 Score Media shares. =
According to the SEC=E2=80=99s complaint, Score Media=E2=80=99s stock price=
 increased nearly 80 percent after Penn National and Score Media publicly a=
nnounced their deal, following which Roda and Larkin sold their holdings fo=
r unlawful profits of $560,762 and $5,602, respectively.And there are the u=
sual bad text messages:Following the announcement, on August 5, 2021, using=
 the encrypted messaging app, Roda sent Larkin a screen shot of the value o=
f the options he purchased. Larkin responded, =E2=80=9CHoly sh*t.=E2=80=9D =
Unsatisfied with the illicit profits he had made, Roda responded that he =
=E2=80=9Cshould=E2=80=99ve gone harder.=E2=80=9DIn another message on Augus=
t, 5, 2021, Larkin suggested that Roda could use the money to purchase a be=
ach house. Roda responded, =E2=80=9Cya if the SEC doesn=E2=80=99t come take=
 it and put me in jail.=E2=80=9DWell, I am sorry to be pedantic, but techni=
cally the SEC can=E2=80=99t put you in jail. The SEC can only seek civil pe=
nalties; you only go to prison if federal prosecutors bring a parallel crim=
inal case.=C2=A0They did though.
 =20
   =20
      Mergers and acquisitions
   =20
 =20
We  talked yesterday about the fact that sometimes acquirers agree to buy c=
ompanies, and then the market crashes before the deal closes, and they get =
cold feet. Since the market has been crashing recently, and since there are=
 several high-profile acquisitions pending (oh fine there=E2=80=99s one, it=
=E2=80=99s Twitter), this is a topic of renewed interest these days, and we=
 discussed the strategies that acquirers can use to wriggle out of deals an=
d that targets can use to keep them in deals.Here is a paper from Davidson =
Heath and Mark Mitchell about =E2=80=9CMarket Returns and Interim Risk in M=
ergers,=E2=80=9D which examines patterns of how deals get renegotiated as m=
arkets go up and down:A primary concern in mergers and acquisitions is the =
risk the deal may be cancelled before it is completed. We document that thi=
s =E2=80=9Cinterim risk=E2=80=9D varies asymmetrically with the aggregate m=
arket return. Deals tend to be renegotiated when the market rises but cance=
lled when the market crashes. These effects are conditional on the method o=
f payment and the contracting stage of the deal, consistent with a mechanis=
m of ex post renegotiation. Variation in interim risk over time alters the =
method of payment in mergers and the firms that are targeted and acquired.I=
n particular, all-cash deals are more likely to get canceled or renegotiate=
d: If Company A agrees to pay $50 per share for Company B, and then the mar=
ket crashes, Company A will want to pay less; if the market goes up, Compan=
y B will want to get more. But if Company A agrees to pay 2.3 of its shares=
 for each share of Company B, and the market goes up or down, the exchange =
ratio will remain roughly fair so there=E2=80=99s no real need to renegotia=
te the deal.One fun result is that the VIX =E2=80=94=C2=A0a measure of shor=
t-term implied equity-market volatility =E2=80=94=C2=A0predicts whether dea=
ls will be more for cash or stock:=C2=A0Finally, motivated by our findings =
on the risk that market crashes pose to deal completion, we examine how the=
 ex ante level of risk affects deal terms. The VIX index measures expected =
future market volatility. We find that controlling for other macroeconomic =
factors =E2=80=93 including the stock market=E2=80=99s price/earnings level=
 =E2=80=93 a higher VIX predicts fewer deals to be paid in cash and a highe=
r deal premium for cash acquisitions. Also, when the VIX is higher, the fir=
ms that are targeted and acquired in cash deals are smaller and have a lowe=
r market beta. These findings have implications for empirical studies of me=
rger activity because they imply that variation in ex ante interim risk als=
o affects the method of payment, the deal premium, and even which firms are=
 targeted and ultimately acquired.If you expect the market to be volatile, =
you try not to do all-cash deals, because the price will probably turn out =
to be wrong one way or the other; doing an all-stock deal gives you more of=
 a margin for error.
 =20
   =20
      Musk Stuff
   =20
 =20
Elsewhere in M&A, here is a fun Financial Times article about how merger ar=
bitrageurs are having fun, or whatever it is that they are having, with Elo=
n Musk=E2=80=99s deal to buy Twitter Inc.:=E2=80=9CThis is an arb traders d=
ream,=E2=80=9D said Felix Lo, portfolio manager at Trium Capital. Musk=E2=
=80=99s erratic tweeting means =E2=80=9Cthere=E2=80=99s practically a news =
item every day. Price fluctuations are good for us.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6M&A a=
rbs typically chase low-risk, market-neutral strategies, and spend time tra=
wling through antitrust issues, legal fine print, political opposition or r=
ival bids. Elon=E2=80=99s id is unfamiliar territory.Gambling on Musk=E2=80=
=99s Twitter deal is a bit like =E2=80=9Cpicking up five dollar bills in fr=
ont of a steamroller with a Ferrari on the back=E2=80=9D, said one arbitrag=
e specialist.I don=E2=80=99t know what the Ferrari is doing in this metapho=
r, or why it is not a Tesla, but you get the idea.One thing that we have ta=
lked about a lot around here, these past few years, is the =E2=80=9CElon Ma=
rkets Hypothesis,=E2=80=9D my dumb idea that some asset prices are driven m=
ore by Elon Musk=E2=80=99s whims than by traditional economic fundamentals.=
 For the most part, the Elon Markets Hypothesis has been confined to a few =
assets =E2=80=94=C2=A0Tesla Inc. stock, Dogecoin =E2=80=94=C2=A0and most se=
rious financial professionals can mostly ignore it. But a dangerous element=
 of the Elon Markets Hypothesis is that Musk himself  gets to pick what ass=
ets it affects. And now the traditional methods of analysis of merger arbit=
rage have been replaced by Elon Merger Arbitrage. The relevant textbooks ha=
ve not yet been written.Elsewhere: =E2=80=9CElon Musk to Participate in Twi=
tter All-Hands Meeting Thursday.=E2=80=9D Does that mean:=09The deal is =E2=
=80=9Cback on,=E2=80=9D or whatever, because he is still working with Twitt=
er=E2=80=99s management to achieve a smooth transition to his ownership; or=
=09He is going to use this as a high-profile occasion to do some more weird=
 stuff to undermine the deal?=C2=A0We=E2=80=99ll find out on Thursday I gue=
ss.=C2=A0
 =20
   =20
      Closing the barn door
   =20
 =20
 Ah:Gary Gensler has a message for people pouring money into crypto on prom=
ises of high returns: beware.The US Securities and Exchange Commission chie=
f on Tuesday repeated his warnings over lending platforms. Gensler said inv=
estors need to be wary of claims of double-digit interest rates.=E2=80=9CTh=
ey=E2=80=99re operating a little bit like banks,=E2=80=9D he said in remark=
s delivered virtually at the RFK Human Rights Compass Summer Investors Conf=
erence. =E2=80=9CI caution the public.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0 Yes.  Well. To be fai=
r, Gensler=E2=80=99s SEC=C2=A0has=C2=A0gone after crypto lending platforms =
 fairly aggressively, even before several of them imploded. If you were put=
ting all your money into a crypto lending protocol, you can=E2=80=99t reall=
y have thought =E2=80=9Cah yes I am sure the SEC approves of this.=E2=80=9D=
 Still the timing is awkward.
