<tr>
<td class=3D"body-component__content" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; m=
so-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt; line-height: 150%; padding: 0 =
10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Bad robot</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In 2015, Charles Schwab Corp. launched=
 a robo-adviser service called Schwab Intelligent Portfolios.=C2=A0SIP woul=
d would invest customers=E2=80=99=C2=A0money for them in a mix of funds opt=
imized for their risk appetite, investment horizon and tax situation. Unlik=
e competing robo-advisers, SIP would not charge customers a fee for this se=
rvice. Instead, it would allocate a bizarrely large portion of their portfo=
lios to cash, and it would keep the cash in a Schwab-affiliated bank accoun=
t paying (initially) 0.1% interest. Schwab could use this cash to earn a hi=
gher rate and keep the difference, making this product profitable for Schwa=
b. Other robo-advisers did not allocate so much to cash, because=C2=A0<em>t=
hey are investing products</em>; most customers keep their cash in bank acc=
ounts and want their investments to be invested. But the other robo-adviser=
s charged fees.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Schwab=E2=80=99s approach w=
as good marketing, but bad for investors: You=E2=80=99d rather be 100% in t=
he market while this was going on (2015 through 2018) and pay a fee than be=
 80% in the market and 20% in cash earning nothing. It was also sort of wei=
rdly well-known: I remember it being controversial at the time, and here is=
 a good New York Times article by Tara Siegel Bernard from March 2015, when=
 SIP launched, headlined =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/28054388.266603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20vMjAxNS8wMy8=
wNi9idXNpbmVzcy9zY2h3YWJzLXNlcnZpY2UtZm9yLWludmVzdG9ycy1zZWVraW5nLXRocmlmdH=
ktYWR2aWNlLXJhaXNlcy1leWVicm93cy5odG1s/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc140e0b9" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;">Schwab=E2=80=99s Service for Investors Seeking Thrifty Advice Raises=
 Eyebrows</a>=E2=80=9D and laying out the problem clearly. But Schwab was c=
agey about it, saying that actually those cash allocations were intended to=
 be good for customers rather than just to make a buck.</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">Yesterday=C2=A0Schwab=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/28054388.266603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZ=
XNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMi0xMDQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB479c7d65" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">agree=
d to pay $187 million</a> to settle US Securities and Exchange Commission c=
harges for deceiving investors over SIP, and the <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28054388.266603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9s=
aXRpZ2F0aW9uL2FkbWluLzIwMjIvMzQtOTUwODcucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB93305=
057" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">SEC order</a> is just so embarrassing:</p><blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Each of SIP=E2=80=99s model portfolios held between 6%=
 and 29.4% of clients=E2=80=99 assets in cash. The amount of cash that each=
 SIP model portfolio contained was pre-set so that Respondents=E2=80=99 aff=
iliate bank would earn at least a minimum amount of revenue from the spread=
 on the cash by loaning out the money. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
In order to offer SIP without charging an advisory fee, Schwab management d=
ecided that the SIP portfolios would collectively hold an average of at lea=
st 12.5% of their assets in cash. To meet that goal, management set the exa=
ct amount of cash in each of SIP=E2=80=99s model portfolios, with the most =
aggressive portfolio containing 6% cash and the most conservative portfolio=
 29.4%, based in large part on its analysis that Schwab Bank would make a m=
inimum amount of revenue at these levels. Management then provided these pr=
e-set cash allocations to CSIA. In building the SIP model portfolios, CSIA =
treated the cash allocations provided by management as constraints and did =
not alter or adjust the cash allocations in any way. ...</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">On February 18, 2015, weeks before the SIP launch, two articl=
es were published in the media that were critical of SIP, claiming that the=
 drag from the high cash allocations was a hidden cost of the program. In r=
eaction to these articles, Schwab management directed that the SWIA ADV bro=
chure be re-written, and that a public relations campaign be launched to ex=
plain the SIP cash allocations. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">While the ADV brochures disclosed that Schwab Bank earned income from =
the cash allocation for each investment strategy, SWIA=E2=80=99s and CSIA=
=E2=80=99s ADV brochures stated that the cash allocations in the SIP portfo=
lios were =E2=80=9Cset based on a disciplined portfolio construction method=
ology designed to balance performance with risk management appropriate for =
a client=E2=80=99s goal, investing time frame, and personal risk tolerance,=
 just as with other Schwab managed products.=E2=80=9D This was false and mi=
sleading because the cash allocations were actually pre-set in order to rea=
ch minimum revenue targets for the Respondents.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know. They got so close, you know? =
It is such a basic move in finance: Find a way to do a valuable thing=C2=A0=
without charging for it explicitly, because you have found a way to charge =
for it implicitly. Schwab=C2=A0<em>could=C2=A0</em>have done this in a more=
 or less legal way: Say =E2=80=9Cwe will charge zero fees and=C2=A0construc=
t a portfolio for you using a disciplined methodology that is appropriate f=
or your goals, period, new sentence,=C2=A0also we will allocate a portion o=
f your money to cash for other reasons.=E2=80=9D And then, when people writ=
e articles about how the cash allocation is too high and represents a big f=
ee for Schwab,=C2=A0<em>just ignore them</em>. Who cares! Some people will =
read the articles and not use SIP; Schwab probably would not attract those =
people by lying anyway. Some people will read the articles=C2=A0<em>and sti=
ll use SIP</em>, thinking =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t like explicit fees and h=
aving a cash drag seems fine.=E2=80=9D (Doesn=E2=80=99t a cash drag seem li=
ke a good idea this month?) Many, many people will not read the articles at=
 all, and those people will be attracted by the zero explicit fees and not =
worry about the implicit ones.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Really Schwa=
b=E2=80=99s mistake was pride: It had figured out a way to hide fees in an =
investment product, people noticed and said =E2=80=9Chey there are hidden f=
ees,=E2=80=9D and Schwab=E2=80=99s management got mad and publicly pretende=
d that those hidden fees were something else. Seems unnecessary. Just smile=
 and say =E2=80=9Cwell we all have to make money somehow=E2=80=9D and trust=
 that you=E2=80=99ve hidden the fees well enough for most customers.</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also I should say that this is a problem that I k=
new about in 2015, because I read the New York Times? It is nice that the S=
EC got $187 million back for investors who were tricked by this, but could =
they not have done it faster?</p><table class=3D"liveintent-sponsored-conte=
